# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To solve this question we can first think about solving a simpler problem, suppose that cost of all the elements are given as 1. 

After solving this simpler problem we can convert the current problem to a variation of the solved problem, let us suppose the given array is [ 1, 3, 5, 2 ] and the given cost array is [ 2, 3, 1, 6 ]  (*The test case has been changed a little for easy representation*)

Like in the smaller problem we sort the array and maintain the order of costs as well, which then gives us :
Array : [1, 2, 3, 5]
Cost  : [2, 6, 3, 1]

Now we can convert this given array into an array with all elements with cost 1, which gives us the array
Array : [1,1,2,2,2,2,2,2,3,3,3,5] 

From this array we can figure out that the number of elements in this array will be the total sum of cost array, from this we can figure out where the median lies in the original array, and then we run a function to calculate the min cost to make our array equal to the median.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach follows the intuition, where we create a vector of integer pairs, with the array element as its first member and the cost as its second member, then we sort this vector of pairs.

Next we simply check that if the expanded array will have even elements or odd elements, in case of even elements we return the minimum cost calculated using both median elements. 

# Note

It is important to note that the value of cost multiplied by the difference in the array elements may exceed the integer limit, so it is crucial that we store these in long long variables instead of integers, otherwise the value of integer will overflow.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n*log(n))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Making the vector of pairs : O(n)
Sorting the vector of pairs : O(n*log(n))
Search the median element : O(n/2)
For caclulating the cost : O(n)

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    unsigned long long costcalc(int target, vector<pair<int,int>> &vec)
    {
        unsigned long long res = 0, res2, res3;
        for(int i = 0; i<vec.size(); i++)
        {
            res2= (abs(target-vec[i].first)) ;
            res3 = vec[i].second;
            res = res+res2*res3;
        }
        return res;
    }

    long long minCost(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cost) {
        vector<pair<int,int>> vec;
        long long sum = 0, sum2;
        for(int i = 0; i<nums.size(); i++)
        {
            sum+=cost[i];
            vec.push_back(make_pair(nums[i], cost[i]));
        }
        sort(vec.begin(), vec.end());
        if(sum%2)
        {
            sum2 = 0;
            for(int i = 0; i<nums.size(); i++)
            {
                sum2+=vec[i].second;
                if(sum2>(sum/2))
                {
                    return costcalc(vec[i].first, vec);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        else
        {
            sum2 = 0; 
            for(int i = 0; i<nums.size(); i++)
            {
                sum2+=vec[i].second;
                if(sum2==sum/2)
                {
                    return min( costcalc( vec[i].first, vec ), costcalc( vec[i+1].first, vec ) );
                    break;
                }
                if(sum2>sum/2)
                {
                    return costcalc(vec[i].first,vec);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return 0;
    }
};
```
