# Intuition
Binary Search approach is not intuitive at first glance but when you try to plot the graph of f(x) (f(x) returns the cost of making all elements equal to x), you'll notice that f(x) is convex and sum of convex functions is also convex.
F(x) = f1(x) + f2(x)............. is also convex. So we can apply binary search.

# Approach
We'll apply binary search in range [min(nums),max(nums)], we can decrease the search space by calculating values of f(mid) and f(mid+1) and if f(mid) < f(mid+1) then e = mid-1 else s = mid+1.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(NlogN)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    #define ll long long
public:
    long long minCost(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cost) {
        int e = *max_element(nums.begin(),nums.end()), s = *min_element(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        ll ans = 0;
        while(s<=e) {
            int mid = s + (e-s)/2;
            ll val1 = f(nums,cost,mid), val2 = f(nums,cost,mid+1);
            ans = min(val1,val2);
            if(val1 < val2) {
                e = mid-1;
            }else s = mid+1;
        }
        return ans;
    }

    ll f(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cost, int x) {
        ll ans = 0;
        for(int i=0 ; i<nums.size() ; ++i) {
            ans += abs(nums[i]-x)*1ll*cost[i];
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

