# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It is although pretty easy to do a O(n^2) solution by traversing the array for each index and finding the minimum cost. Hence to run it down to a O(n) solution, it was intuitive to iterate through the array from start to end only once while updating the answer according to the minimum cost each time.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
In order to make sure the array is only iterated through once, the nums is sorted so that from moving from an index to its right, a sum of all the costs from the left multiplied by the current difference is added, as the current nums is increasing. The current difference is a variable named curr in the code.
 Similarly, the sum of costs to the right is multiplied by the current difference as all those costs will decrease if nums increases and is hence subtracted. A variable named now will be updated to prev each time through the loop as the changes are continuous and with respect to the last value.
For this, a pair of vectors is sorted with the nums as the first of the pair.
Two prefix sum arrays are used to have the left and right sums for an index.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long minCost(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cost) {
        vector<pair<long long,long long>> v;
        int n=nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            v.push_back({nums[i],cost[i]});
        }
        sort(v.begin(),v.end());
        long long ans=0;
        long long pfix1[n+1],pfix2[n+1];
        pfix1[0]=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            pfix1[i+1]=pfix1[i]+v[i].second;
        }
        pfix2[n]=0;
        for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--){
            pfix2[i]=pfix2[i+1]+v[i].second;
        }
        //initial ans in order to update in next iteration.
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            ans+=(v[i].first-v[0].first)*v[i].second;
        }
        long long f=v[0].first;
        long long prev,now; //now will be updated to prev each time.
        prev=ans;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            long long curr=v[i].first-f; //curr is the difference in nums each time 
            now=prev;
            now+=pfix1[i]*curr;
            now-=pfix2[i]*curr;
            ans=min(ans,now);
            prev=now;
            f=v[i].first;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

