# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This problem is a bit similar to the problem for finding minimum cost to make array equal with each having the equal cost.
Difference here is that the array is weighted.

We can write array:
nums = [1,3,5,2] 
cost = [2,3,1,14]
as:-
nums = [1,1,3,3,3,5,2,2,2,......14 times]

Means the cost represents the count of that number in array.

So now it became the same problem array with same and equal cost = 1. 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Approach is simple....
If cost is equal for incrementing/decrementing the element.

Now we have to make all elements equal.
so Sort the nums such that cost will be arranged in their respective way too. 
now From two extremes position we will meet at the median.
And we will make all element = median for minimum cost.
thus:- 
Cost for changing a element at index i:- **abs(nums[i]-median)*cost[i]**;
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlog(n))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long minCost(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cost) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<pair<int,int>> v;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            v.push_back({nums[i],cost[i]});
        }
        sort(v.begin(),v.end());
        long long sum = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            sum += v[i].second;
        }
        sum = (sum + 1)/2;
        long long total = 0;
        int i = 0;
        long long median;
        while(total<sum && i<n)
        {
            total+=v[i].second;
            median = v[i].first;
            i++;
        }
        long long ans = 0;
        for(i= 0;i<n;i++)
        {
            ans+=1L * abs(v[i].first-median) * v[i].second;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
