# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
* The goal is to make all the elements of the array nums equal while minimizing the total cost. 
* To achieve this, we need to identify the target value that we want all elements to become. 
* We can find this target value by sorting the elements based on their values and finding the midpoint. 
* Once we have the target value, we calculate the cost required to make each element equal to the target value and return the total cost.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize variables: n as the size of the arrays nums and cost, v as a vector of pairs to store elements from nums and cost, and totalCost as the sum of all elements in the cost array.
2. Iterate through the elements of nums and cost simultaneously. For each index i, store the pair (nums[i], cost[i]) in the vector v and add cost[i] to totalCost.
3. Sort the vector v in ascending order based on the first element of each pair (the values from nums).
4. Calculate the midpoint mid by adding 1 to totalCost and dividing it by 2.
5. Initialize target as -1 and currSum as 0.
6. Iterate through the elements of v. For each element, add its cost to currSum. If currSum becomes greater than or equal to mid, set target as the first element (the value from nums) of the current pair and break out of the loop.
7. Initialize ans as 0.
8. Iterate through the elements of nums. For each element at index i, calculate the absolute difference between nums[i] and target, multiply it by cost[i], and add the result to ans.
9. Return the value of ans.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(nlogn)$$

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
# Code

