# Intuition
Let say I want to make the all the elements equals to `nums[i]` then I have to increment all elements smaller then `nums[i]` and decrement elements greater than `nums[i]` and let say total cost required is $$X^i$$ then minmum of $$X^i$$'s for all values of _i_ will be my answer.

can we find total cost required to make all elements equals to _i_ in costant time?

Yes we can by maintaing prefix and sufix array's.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(NlogN)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Video Explanation 
 Watch Youtube Video to understand the intuition, approach and explanation of the problem 

[https://youtu.be/D6PLV93_1P8]() 

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long minCost(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cost) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<pair<int ,int>> v;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            v.push_back({nums[i], cost[i]});
        }
        sort(v.begin(),v.end());

        vector<long long> preCostSum(n, 0), sufCostSum(n, 0);
        vector<long long> preProdSum(n, 0), sufProdSum(n , 0);

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            if(i > 0)
            {
                preCostSum[i] += preCostSum[i-1];
                preProdSum[i] += preProdSum[i-1];
            }
            preCostSum[i] += v[i].second;
            preProdSum[i] += (1LL*v[i].first * v[i].second);
        }

        for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--)
        {
            if(i < n-1)
            {
                sufCostSum[i] += sufCostSum[i+1];
                sufProdSum[i] += sufProdSum[i+1];
            }
            sufCostSum[i] += v[i].second;
            sufProdSum[i] += (1LL*v[i].first * v[i].second);
        }

        long long ans = 1e18;
        for(int i=0;i<n-1;i++)
        {
            long long temp = v[i].first*preCostSum[i] - preProdSum[i] - v[i].first*sufCostSum[i+1] + sufProdSum[i+1];
            ans = min(ans, temp);
        }
        long long temp = v[n-1].first*preCostSum[n-1] - preProdSum[n-1];
        ans = min(ans, temp);
        return ans; 
    }
};
```

